WEBVTT

0
00:00:03.059 --> 00:00:03.690
For decades,

1
00:00:03.819 --> 00:00:07.530
data centers relied on a simple principle to keep servers from melting down.

2
00:00:07.739 --> 00:00:09.479
Push cold air in the front

3
00:00:09.579 --> 00:00:11.369
and blow hot air out the back.

4
00:00:12.069 --> 00:00:15.000
But with the sheer density of modern AI silicon,

5
00:00:15.279 --> 00:00:16.700
air cooling has hit a wall.

6
00:00:18.409 --> 00:00:21.200
The heat cannot and transport fast enough.

7
00:00:22.069 --> 00:00:24.889
Air is simply a terrible conductor of heat.

8
00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:29.979
Liquid can capture and transport thousands of times more efficiently than air.

9
00:00:30.729 --> 00:00:33.540
To support AI clusters pushing 100 kilowatts or

10
00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:36.139
more compared to the standard 12 kilowatt rack.

11
00:00:37.569 --> 00:00:41.569
The OCP Cooling Environments project had to shift the industry standards.

12
00:00:42.599 --> 00:00:44.930
This transition happens in stages.

13
00:00:45.400 --> 00:00:48.909
For facilities that are not ready to pipe water directly into the servers,

14
00:00:49.169 --> 00:00:51.270
we use rear door heat exchangers,

15
00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:52.000
RDX.

16
00:00:52.959 --> 00:00:54.360
These come in two forms.

17
00:00:54.639 --> 00:00:57.200
Passive simply uses the liquid-filled coil.

18
00:00:57.819 --> 00:01:01.759
Active includes a fan wall to assist in the heat transfer,

19
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:02.959
combining air

20
00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:04.940
and liquid cooling into one.

21
00:01:06.260 --> 00:01:08.860
The incredible success of the Open Reck V3

22
00:01:08.860 --> 00:01:12.199
is driven by 3 main hardware standardizations.

23
00:01:14.010 --> 00:01:15.370
The 21 inch width,

24
00:01:15.809 --> 00:01:17.489
the centralized power buzz bar,

25
00:01:17.730 --> 00:01:19.690
and the liquid manifold stayout zone.

26
00:01:21.629 --> 00:01:25.279
Every ORV3 rec reserves a dedicated standardized

27
00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:27.919
physical space strictly for liquid manifolds.

28
00:01:29.099 --> 00:01:31.730
In an industry with very few liquid standards,

29
00:01:31.980 --> 00:01:36.139
this provides a predictable plug and play architecture for fluid delivery.

30
00:01:37.989 --> 00:01:40.089
This standardized manifold space

31
00:01:40.349 --> 00:01:43.629
perfectly enables direct liquid cooling or DOC.

32
00:01:45.279 --> 00:01:50.040
Metal cold plates with microchannels are mounted right on top of the CPU and GPUs.

33
00:01:51.220 --> 00:01:54.410
Using high reliability zero leak fluid connectors,

34
00:01:54.760 --> 00:01:57.260
the wreck mounted manifold safely pumps a water

35
00:01:57.260 --> 00:01:59.379
and glyco mix directly to the silicon.

36
00:02:01.339 --> 00:02:01.800
This

37
00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:05.599
captures up to 80% of the heat exactly where it's generated.

38
00:02:06.489 --> 00:02:10.369
While liquid cooling maximizes the potential of the standard OV3 rack.

39
00:02:11.699 --> 00:02:16.179
Our ultimate solution requires a completely different physical architecture,

40
00:02:16.419 --> 00:02:17.399
immersiont cooling.

41
00:02:18.729 --> 00:02:21.350
Instead of sliding it into a vertical rack,

42
00:02:21.690 --> 00:02:24.369
entire servers are now completely submerged into

43
00:02:24.369 --> 00:02:28.089
a horizontal tank of nonconductive dialectic fluid.

44
00:02:29.190 --> 00:02:29.199
Because

45
00:02:29.550 --> 00:02:31.929
the fluid physically touches every component,

46
00:02:32.139 --> 00:02:33.229
CPU GPU,

47
00:02:33.350 --> 00:02:34.429
memory and network,

48
00:02:34.789 --> 00:02:37.509
there are no blind mate manifolds or hoses required.

49
00:02:39.339 --> 00:02:40.429
In a single phase,

50
00:02:40.589 --> 00:02:42.110
the fluid absorbs the heat.

51
00:02:44.919 --> 00:02:46.199
In a two-phase,

52
00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:48.949
the extreme heat actually boils the fluid,

53
00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:51.960
and the resulting phase change allows the vapor to

54
00:02:51.960 --> 00:02:54.960
condense and cool the hardware at an unmatched scale.

55
00:02:56.600 --> 00:02:57.899
Whether it's cold plate

56
00:02:58.039 --> 00:02:59.440
or a full immersion tank,

57
00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:02.270
liquid cooling is no longer a science experiment,

58
00:03:02.559 --> 00:03:04.320
it's a survival requirement.

59
00:03:05.470 --> 00:03:06.690
Now the hardware is built,

60
00:03:06.910 --> 00:03:08.149
the specs are published,

61
00:03:08.509 --> 00:03:10.830
the only thing left to do is to deploy it.